allow setting --url <custom_site_url> from commandline (issue #15, closes #143)Sometimes you may be forced to use absolute urls. For example I had problem with FeedBurner's blog post preview page. Image links specified as relative urls were not resolved correctly. I can imagine some poor RSS readers may behave similar way.nnI wanted site.url to be configurable, because I didn't want to hard-code final url there. I still want to be able to have working link when doing local web site development and testing. I have small bash script which runs jekyll -serve --auto with this parameter set for local development. My setup is more complicated, because I use several jekylls behind reverse proxy to simulate setup on http://binaryage.com which uses gh-pages from many repos together with layouts linked as git modules.n

faster_lsi: Massively accelerate LSI performance.Currently, Classifier::LSI rebuilds the index every time an entry isnadded.  This runs into massive performance overheads on my website;ntheoretically, disabling automatic index rebuilds, and explicitlynrebuilding the LSI index at the end of the LSI repopulation shouldnspeed things up nicely.nnAs a side note, here, I use pandoc-ruby to provide a more featurefulnMarkdown transformer, so be mindful that the numbers I quote here havenartifically imposed I/O overheads.nnWith just the 76 posts I wrote this year (abysmal, I know), I come upnwith the following figures:nnWithout faster_lsi:n  jekyll --lsi  16.91s user 0.88s system 97% cpu 18.302 totalnWith faster_lsi:n  jekyll --lsi  2.72s user 0.77s system 88% cpu 3.940 totalnnWith 109 posts, we begin to see even better improvements:nnWithout faster_lsi:n  jekyll --lsi  51.00s user 1.47s system 98% cpu 53.060 totalnWith faster_lsi:n  jekyll --lsi  5.04s user 1.12s system 91% cpu 6.735 totalnnAt this point, we begin to see I/O overheads being slower than LSInwhen faster_lsi is active.  I call that fairly conclusive.  But wait,nthere's more.  I have 273 posts lying around... I wonder what happensnif I feed them all in.  With faster_lsi, it was nice and clippy.nWithout it, I simply gave up, and went and refilled my cup of tea.nAnd it was still going.nnWithout faster_lsi:n  jekyll --lsi  1277.86s user 10.90s system 99% cpu 21:30.29 totalnWith faster_lsi:n  jekyll --lsi  34.62s user 4.43s system 96% cpu 40.430 totalnnThat is, in anyone's books, a major improvement.  Note, however, thatnI don't know just how well this will perform with `jekyll --auto`nbecause I don't know how it does the LSI rebuilds.  I _think_ (butnplease, don't commit me on this) that the LSI is rebuilt every timenJekyll picks up a file change.nnSo, all up, the performance improvement is massive, and scalesndepending on how many files you have.  At the last point, thenimprovement is just on 3200%.nnA more optimal solution would be to cache the LSI index and/or contentndata somehow.  I'll leave that to when faster_lsi takes over tennminutes to run.n

Moving Quick-start guide to own sectionAs a new user to jekyll I wanted to get up and running as quickly as possible.nnThe first thing I did was jump to the docs (missing the example on the homepage - my bad) and look for the quick start guide. Since I couldn't find one I went for the 'Basic Usage' section. I ended up muddling around for about 10 minutes until I hit the home page again to see the simple - and very easy - example of how to get started.nnSo, in this pull request I've moved the Quick-start Guide out to it's own section so that users who really are impatient (like me) can clearly look for and jump to the quick start guide, follow the super-easy steps, and be up and running in a matter of minutes.nnInterested to hear if this is thought of as being a good idea.

Fix 'undefined method `encoding` for mailto' errors w/ Ruby 1.8 and Kramdown > 0.14.0When using Ruby 1.8.7 and Kramdown 0.14.0 and newer, the following build errornwould occur if any page in your site contained a `<name@example.com>` emailnaddress link:nnGenerating...   Conversion error: There was an error converting 'contribute.markdown'.n/Users/nick/Documents/puppet-docs/vendor/bundle/ruby/1.8/gems/kramdown-1.0.2/lib/kramdown/converter/html.rb:404:in `obfuscate': undefined method `encoding' for mailto:String (NoMethodError)nnSee also:nhttp://rubyforge.org/tracker/index.php?func=detail&aid=29750&group_id=7403&atid=28673nnThis problem traced back to the following line in the Kramdown source:nnresult.force_encoding(text.encoding) if result.respond_to?(:force_encoding)nnStrings aren't supposed to respond to the :force_encoding method in Ruby < 1.9,nbut lib/jekyll/core_ext.rb was modifying the string class like so:nndef force_encoding(enc)n  selfnendnnStrings still won't respond to :encoding, though, so we get an error whennKramdown tries to read the incoming encoding and everything will blow up.nnAn ack of the codebase suggests that this was only added so we could force annencoding for rdiscount on 1.9 without having to check whether we were runningnunder 1.8. Since testing for said method to learn whether one is running under an1.9-like encoding regime seems to be a thing in libraries we rely on, wenshouldn't insert this dummy method without also dummying every other part of thenRuby 1.9+ encoding system.nnThis commit removes the dummy :force_encoding method to stop poisoning corenclasses for libraries we use, and moves the adjustment for 1.9-like encodingnregimes to the one place where it's needed.n

always include file extension on destination filesThis ensures that destination files for HTML posts, pages andncollections always include the proper file extension (as defined bynoutput_ext) regardless of permalink structure.  This allows for URLsnthat contain no extension or trailing slash to still result in properndestination files with .html extensions.nnBecause this change relies so heavily on output_ext accuratelynidentifying the extension of the destination file, this change alsonremoves the feature test that tested support for permalinks with a .htmnextension.  In order to support alternate file extensions, a futurenpatch or plugin will need to modify the output_ext value, at which pointneverything else should work as expected.n

Improved permalinks for pages and collectionsThis updates the default permalink style for pages and collections tonmatch the site-wide 'permalink' setting.  If the permalink settingncontains a trailing slash, either explicitly or by being set ton':pretty', then pages and collections permalinks will contain trailingnslashes by default as well.  Similarly, if the permalink settingncontains a trailing ':output_ext', so will pages and collections.  Ifnthe permalink setting contains neither a trailing slash or extension,nneither will pages or collections.nnThis impacts only the default permalink structure for pages andncollections.  Permalinks set in the frontmatter of an individual pagentake precedence, as does the permalink setting for a specificncollection.nnFixes #2691n

Use `Jekyll::Post`s for both LSI indexing and lookup.When looking for related posts, Jekyll was indexing `Jekyll::Post`nobjects, but finding related posts based on `Jekyll::Post#content`. Thisncaused two problems:nn1. Ruby 2.2 will warn on == if <=> throws an exception (and future Rubynversions will surface that exception). Because `String`s can't bencompared with `Jekyll::Post`s, this warning was appearing all the timenwhile searching for related posts.nn2. LSI won't return a post itself when searching for related posts. ButnLSI could never tell that we were searching on a post, since Jekyllnpassed post content, not a post object. With this fix, we can remove then`- [post]` from `Jekyll::RelatedPosts#find_related`.nnThis is a more accurate fix for #3484.n

Added my site for learning purposesA week ago, I asked @parkr via email if he could add my site here (mostly because I thought it's too cheeky to just propose a file-change). But now he told me that it's better to just do it here:rnrnI'm asking because I spend a huge amount of time and effort on making it great and usefully structured for people who're just getting started with Jekyll. Therefore it's also great as a forked starting-point, if you ask me.rnrnBesides keeping the code clean, I also spend much time on making the site as fast as possible. There's not much CSS in use, the HTML output is minified and images are directly served from the repo (and therefore GitHub's CDN) instead of from third-party services. There's also a lot of include-thinking happening for things like embedded Tweets, images or iFrames - which most people just inline in each post.rnrnWhen making a significant change, I also always make sure to write a few paragraphs about why I exactly did it as a commit message. And when it comes to really big updates, I write entire posts too (explaining all improvements and their benefits to the site's performance/look). Here's an recent example: http://leo.github.io/notes/v2/rnrnI'm definitely sure that many people could get something out of it. Don't you think so too?

Whole-post excerpts should match the post contentWhen a post does not contain an excerpt_separator, meaning the excerptnincludes the entire post, the excerpt should contain exactly the postncontent.nnThis is desirable both from a correctness standpoint, that the excerptnshould not introduce any new content, and more practically to allow fastnand easy detection of whole-post excerpts in Liquid templates usingn`post.excerpt == post.content`.  A common use-case is deciding whethernto render Read More links on a page containing post excerpts.nnThis commit does exactly that.  It avoids adding additional newlines tonthe excerpt content when the excerpt includes the whole post and addsntests to ensure that this behavior is correct and preserved goingnforward.nnSigned-off-by: Kevin Locke <kevin@kevinlocke.name>n

Initial work on using Liquid::Drops instead of Hashes.The properties of Liquid::Drops are only evaluated when they're asked fornand therefore save computation time. This prevents a lot of GC time cleaningnup objects that are not needed, because they're not created unless requested.nAdditionally, this saves time for actual computation of those values becausenthey can be computed only if needed.nnIt's funny how much it helps when you only do what is needed. Add installing devel libraries to fedoraI followed the troubleshooting and came up with `sudo gem install jekyll` unable to generate the binary file because the development libraries were not installed on my system. Per [fedoraproject.org -- Gems](https://developer.fedoraproject.org/tech/languages/ruby/gems-installation.html) this is necessary to install this. The instructions mirror what is listed on that page, but using `yum` instead of `dnf` - which is understandable because RH and CentOS still use `yum`.

Additional repo needed for Fedora 23 WorkspaceAfter running:rnrnsudo dnf install ruby ruby-devel rubygems nodejsrnsudo dnf group install C Development and ToolsrnrnI was unable to install Jekyll via `gem` due to an error:rnrnThe compiler failed to generate an executable file. (RuntimeError) You have to install development tools first.rnrnTaken from the [fedoraproject.org](https://developer.fedoraproject.org/tech/languages/ruby/gems-installation.html) Gem page:rnrn>If you installed all the above, but the extensions would still not compile, you are probably running a Fedora image that misses `redhat-rpm-config` >package. In that case gcc compiler would complain about one of the following:rnrngcc: error: conftest.c: No such file or directoryrngcc: error: /usr/lib/rpm/redhat/redhat-hardened-cc1: No such file or directoryrnrn>To solve this, simply run sudo dnf install `redhat-rpm-config`.rnrnAfter doing so it downloaded, compiled and installed without a problem.

Fix #4856: Don't rescue LoadError or bundler load errors for Bundler.When it comes to bundler it's smart enough to know what to require, and in casees it's not, it's smart enough to accept :require.  In most cases when bundler has a LoadError (or otherwise) it's because there is a problem inside of the Gem itself and when this happens, Jekyll will happily let that error slip when it shouldn't, resulting in a badly placed error that is actually wrong. This corrects that so errors can surface properly.n

Sort the results of the require_all glob.Filesystems behave differently when performing glob listings.nnIn my environment, they are listed alphabetically. On my Mac, when asking for a list of files in a directory, those files are returned as a nicely sorted list. Alphabetized, like you'd want them to be. Like you'd expect them to be.nnIn some environments, quite different from my own, the return of a similar operation is quite random. Perhaps q comes before a, or e before d; the filesystem will choose its order of the day and you, the fare user, tired and weary from work, must bare the brunt of this.nnAnd so, with this commit, I do hereby request that the noble makers of Dir[] provide for us, the downtrodden and ravaged users, some consistency. As a user of Ruby, I shouldn't have to know or consider the behaviour of an individual filesystem here; it should function the same for all filesystems.nnTruly yours,nParkern

Documentation on how to build navigationI added a documentation page on how to build navigation for your site. This topic is primarily intended for users who have a lot of pages on their site (such as for documentation websites), and want to build a more robust sidebar navigation.rnrnJekyll combines Liquid with YAML in interesting ways that aren't really documented clearly in the existing docs, except for a brief reference [here](http://jekyllrb.com/docs/datafiles/#the-data-folder). You can read about Liquid on Shopify and YAML in YAML's docs, but exactly how you store YAML files in a Jekyll project and iterate through them using Liquid loops and filters to generate lists of pages is something that isn't clear to a lot of people. (You can see origins of these questions in [previous help issues](https://github.com/jekyll/jekyll-help/issues/266).)  The documentation on navigation would fit well into the Jekyll docs.

Makes uri_escape template docs more specific.I didn't know the difference between cgi_escape and uri_escape until it bit me when I had a colon in a title I used uri_escape on. Addressable::URI.encode (from addressable 2.4.0 and later) thought it was a URI and raised an error. I should have been using cgi_escape, which is for strings that will be added to URIs and not uri_escape, which is for encoding strings that are already in a URI.nnThis commit borrows from the addressable docs to make it more specific so that readers choose uri_escape when they already have a URI and cgi_escape when they are just escaping a plain string.n
